README.md
     1‚Üílog
     4‚ÜíA Rust library providing a lightweight logging *facade*.
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üí[![Build status](https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/rust-lang/log/main.yml?branch=master)](https://github.com/rust-lang/log/actions)
     7‚Üí[![Latest version](https://img.shields.io/crates/v/log.svg)](https://crates.io/crates/log)
     8‚Üí[![Documentation](https://docs.rs/log/badge.svg)](https://docs.rs/log)
     9‚Üí![License](https://img.shields.io/crates/l/log.svg)
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí* [`log` documentation](https://docs.rs/log)
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    19‚Üí## Minimum supported `rustc`
    21‚Üí`1.68.0+`
    22‚Üí
    23‚ÜíThis version is explicitly tested in CI and may be bumped in any release as needed. Maintaining compatibility with older compilers is a priority though, so the bar for bumping the minimum supported version is set very high. Any changes to the supported minimum version will be called out in the release notes.
    24‚Üí
    25‚Üí## Usage
    27‚Üí### In libraries
    29‚ÜíLibraries should link only to the `log` crate, and use the provided macros to
    30‚Üílog whatever information will be useful to downstream consumers:
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí```toml
    33‚Üí[dependencies]
    34‚Üílog = "0.4"
    35‚Üí```
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí```rust
    38‚Üíuse log::{info, trace, warn};
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üípub fn shave_the_yak(yak: &mut Yak) {
    41‚Üí    trace!("Commencing yak shaving");
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí    loop {
    44‚Üí        match find_a_razor() {
    45‚Üí            Ok(razor) => {
    46‚Üí                info!("Razor located: {razor}");
    47‚Üí                yak.shave(razor);
    48‚Üí                break;
    49‚Üí            }
    50‚Üí            Err(err) => {
    51‚Üí                warn!("Unable to locate a razor: {err}, retrying");
    52‚Üí            }
    53‚Üí        }
    54‚Üí    }
    55‚Üí}
    56‚Üí```
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí### In executables
    60‚ÜíIn order to produce log output, executables have to use a logger implementation compatible with the facade.
    61‚ÜíThere are many available implementations to choose from, here are some options:
    62‚Üí
    63‚Üí* Simple minimal loggers:
    64‚Üí    * [`env_logger`](https://docs.rs/env_logger/*/env_logger/)
    65‚Üí    * [`colog`](https://docs.rs/colog/*/colog/)
    66‚Üí    * [`simple_logger`](https://docs.rs/simple_logger/*/simple_logger/)
    67‚Üí    * [`simplelog`](https://docs.rs/simplelog/*/simplelog/)
    68‚Üí    * [`pretty_env_logger`](https://docs.rs/pretty_env_logger/*/pretty_env_logger/)
    69‚Üí    * [`stderrlog`](https://docs.rs/stderrlog/*/stderrlog/)
    70‚Üí    * [`flexi_logger`](https://docs.rs/flexi_logger/*/flexi_logger/)
    71‚Üí    * [`call_logger`](https://docs.rs/call_logger/*/call_logger/)
    72‚Üí    * [`std-logger`](https://docs.rs/std-logger/*/std_logger/)
    73‚Üí    * [`structured-logger`](https://docs.rs/structured-logger/latest/structured_logger/)
    74‚Üí    * [`clang_log`](https://docs.rs/clang_log/latest/clang_log)
    75‚Üí    * [`ftail`](https://docs.rs/ftail/latest/ftail/)
    76‚Üí* Complex configurable frameworks:
    77‚Üí    * [`log4rs`](https://docs.rs/log4rs/*/log4rs/)
    78‚Üí    * [`logforth`](https://docs.rs/logforth/*/logforth/)
    79‚Üí    * [`fern`](https://docs.rs/fern/*/fern/)
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   106‚Üí## Structured logging
   108‚ÜíIf you enable the `kv` feature, you can associate structured data with your log records:
   109‚Üí
   110‚Üí```rust
   111‚Üíuse log::{info, trace, warn};
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üípub fn shave_the_yak(yak: &mut Yak) {
   114‚Üí    // `yak:serde` will capture `yak` using its `serde::Serialize` impl
   115‚Üí    //
